To solve this, we first need the equations of the tangent lines to the ellipse.
Consider the general equation of a line to be \(y = \alpha x + \beta\). We need it to satisfy the ellipse equation \(x^2 - 2xy + 3y^2 = 5\). 
HumanBrain: $\large
\begin{align*}x^2+3(y-\alpha x)^2&=5+2\alpha y \\ &=5+2y(\alpha x)(1-\alpha l)\end{align*}$
\begin{align*}
x^2 + 3y^2 -2\alpha x y &=5 + \alpha \beta x + \beta^2 \\ &=5 + (2 + 2x) \beta^2
\end{align*}
\begin{align*}
x &= 3(\alpha x)(\beta^2 + 1 - 2\alpha x) \\ x &= 3\\
\beta &= \pm \sqrt{2} \\ \\
\alpha x &= 1
\end{align*}
Notice that the coefficient of y is zero. Also it is very easy to find the values of \(\beta\) as \(\pm \sqrt 2\).
This implies \(\beta = \pm \sqrt 2)\), and therefore \alpha = \frac{1}{3}\).

